The coefficient of friction between the parcel and the slope is $1/12$. In addition to friction, the parcel experiences a variable resistive force of $mv$ N, where $v \text{ ms}^{-1}$ is the velocity of the parcel at time $t$ seconds.
(a) Show that the motion of the parcel satisfies the differential equation $\frac{dv}{dt} = \frac{g - 5v}{5}$. [5]
(b) Given that the parcel is initially at rest on the slope, find an expression for $v$ in terms of $t$ and $g$. [5]
(c) To avoid damage, the speed of the parcel must be restricted to a maximum of $2 \text{ ms}^{-1}$ down the slope. Determine whether or not the speed of the parcel exceeds $2 \text{ ms}^{-1}$. [1]

**Answer:**
(a) $\cos\alpha = 24/25$. Normal reaction $R = mg\cos\alpha = \frac{24mg}{25}$. Friction $F = \mu R = \frac{1}{12} \times \frac{24mg}{25} = \frac{2mg}{25}$.
Equation of motion: $mg\sin\alpha - F - mv = m\frac{dv}{dt}$.
$mg\left(\frac{7}{25}\right) - \frac{2mg}{25} - mv = m\frac{dv}{dt} \implies \frac{5mg}{25} - mv = m\frac{dv}{dt} \implies \frac{dv}{dt} = \frac{g}{5} - v = \frac{g - 5v}{5}$.
(b) Separating variables: $\int \frac{5}{g - 5v} \, dv = \int 1 \, dt \implies -\ln|g - 5v| = t + C$.
At $t = 0, v = 0 \implies C = -\ln g$.
$-\ln\left(\frac{g - 5v}{g}\right) = t \implies 1 - \frac{5v}{g} = e^{-t} \implies v = \frac{g}{5}(1 - e^{-t})$.
(c) As $t \to \infty$, the maximum speed is $\frac{g}{5} = \frac{9.8}{5} = 1.96 \text{ ms}^{-1}$. Since $1.96 < 2$, the speed does not exceed $2 \text{ ms}^{-1}$.
